Lab setup
	- Network has two subnets
		○ External: 10.8.0.0/24
		○ Internal: 192.168.20.0/24
	- Router firewall connects the two and uses NAT and iptables to control traffic
	- Host IP 10.8.0.1 is not a container but given to the host machine
	- To reach the internet from the hosts in both subnets, packets must be routed to 10.8.0.1
	- HOSTS
		○ Router (firewall) -- 10.8.0.11
		○ A: 10.8.0.5
		○ A1: 10.8.0.6
		○ A2: 10.8.0.99
		○ B: 192.168.20.99
		○ B1: 192.168.20.5
		○ B2: 192.168.20.6

Router Configuration (built in to docker file)
	- NAT rule 
		○ `iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING ! -d 10.8.0.0/24 -j MASQUERADE -o eth0`
		○ Outbound packets have their source replaced by 10.8.0.11
		○ Traffic within 10.8.0.0/24 is untouched
	- Firewall rules
		○ # Ingress: allow SSH only
		○ `iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -p tcp -m conntrack --ctstate ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
		○ iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
		○ iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -p tcp -j DROP
		○ # Egress: block example.com
		○ iptables -A FORWARD -i eth1 -d 93.184.216.0/24 -j DROP
		○ Meaning
			§ Rule 1: allows TCP packets to come from an established connection
			§ Rule 2: allows SSH in bound
			§ Rule 3: drops all other TCP packets
			§ Rule 4: prevents the internal host from sending packets to external host www.example.com
