Task 1: Static Port Forwarding
		○ Use static port forwarding to evade firewall restriction using ssh to create a static port forwarding tunnel between host A (external network) and host B (internal network)
		○ GOAL: expose B1's telnet (192.168.20.5:23) on external A at 10.8.0.5:2222 via an SSH tunnel through B (192.168.20.99). Then capture traffic and identify the three TCP connections involved
	- Start a telnet server on B1
		○ docker exec -it B1-192.168.20.5 bash
		○ ss -ltnp | grep :23
	- Create SSH static port forward on A
		○ docker exec -it A-10.8.0.99 bash
		○ ssh -4NT -L 0.0.0.0:2222:192.168.20.5:23 root@192.168.20.99 &
			§ (yes)
	- Test connectivity from A, A1, and A2
		○ # from host
		○ docker exec -it A1-10.8.0.5 bash
		○ telnet 10.8.0.99 2222
		○ 
	- Repeat on A and A2
		○ #  on A
		○ telnet 127.0.0.1 2222
		○ # on host
		○ docker exec -it A2-10.8.0.6 bash
		○ telnet 10.8.0.99 2222
	- Capture Packets from router
		○ docker exec -it router-firewall bash
		○ tcpdump -i any -n tcp and \(port 22 or port 2222 or port 23\)
		○ Redo the telnet commands for the packets to show up
		○ 

	- Answer to questions
		○ TCP connections
			§ Client --> A (port 2222)
			§ A <--> B (SSH tunnel)
			§ B --> B1 (telnet)
		○ Evades Firewall by encapsulating the telnet traffic inside an SSH connection, the firewall only sees a legitimate SSH session between A and B

Task 2: Dynamic Port Forwarding
	- Goal: use SSH dynamic port forwarding (SOCKS5 proxy) to bypass the egress firewall that blocks certain websites (www.example.com).
	- Confirm Router's Egress Rules
		○ docker exec -it router-firewall bash
		○ iptables -L FORWARD -n -v | grep DROP
		○ 
	- Verify that blocked sites are inaccessible from inside internal network
		○ docker exec -it B1-192.168.20.5 bash
		○ curl http://example.com
	- Create a dynamic SSH tunnel (SOCKS5 proxy)
		○ Making a tunnel from B (192.168.20.99)--> A (10.8.0.99)
		○ docker exec -it B-192.168.20.99 bash
		○ ssh -4NT -D 0.0.0.0:1080 root@10.8.0.99
			§ (yes)
	- Test the tunnel with curl from any internal host
		○ docker exec -it B1-192.168.20.5 bash
		○ curl --proxy socks5h://192.168.20.99:1080 http://example.com
		○ Before and after
			§ 
		○ Same thing for B2
	- Capture Evidence on Router
		○ docker exec -it router-firewall bash
		○ tcpdump -i any -n tcp and \(port 22 or port 1080 or port 80\)
		○ Rerun curl command to see packets
		○ 
		○ tcpdump packets on port 22 showing HTTP traffic encapsulated in SSH tunnel.
		○ The [P.] packets confirm encrypted HTTP data traveling through the SSH tunnel on port 22; no direct HTTP (port 80) packets are visible, demonstrating successful firewall evasion.
	- Answer to Questions
		○ Which computer makes the real connection?
			§ A (10.8.0.99) initiates TCP connection to the web server
		○ How does it know where to connect?
			§ SOCKS5 protocol tells A the destination hostname/IP, B forwards that info through the SSH tunnel
		○ Firewall Bypass 
			§ The egress firewall on 192.168.20.0/24 sees only SSH traffic from B to A so it can't block the tunneled HTTP requests
