Task 2.3: Writing a SOCKS Client Using Python
		○ GOAL: write and run a simple Python script that connects www.example.com through the SOCKS5 proxy running on B (192.168.20.99:1080), retrieves the HTTP header or page, and prints the output
	- Rerun Dynamic SSH tunnel on B 
		○ ssh -4NT -D 0.0.0.0:1080 root@10.8.0.99
	- Install socks module on B1 (if needed)
		○ docker exec -it B1-192.168.20.5 bash
		○ apt-get update
		○ apt-get install -y python3-pip
		○ pip3 install PySocks
	- Create and run the Python SOCKS client in the internal network -- I'm using B1
		○ nano simple_socks_client.py
		#!/usr/bin/env python3
		import socks
		import socket
		
		# Connect via the SOCKS5 proxy running on B
		proxy_ip = "192.168.20.99"
		proxy_port = 1080
		
		target_host = "www.example.com"
		target_port = 80
		
		# Create SOCKS socket and set proxy
		s = socks.socksocket()
		s.set_proxy(socks.SOCKS5, proxy_ip, proxy_port)
		
		# Connect to target through proxy
		s.connect((target_host, target_port))
		
		# Send basic HTTP GET request
		request = (
		    b"GET / HTTP/1.0\r\n"
		    b"Host: www.example.com\r\n"
		    b"User-Agent: Python-SOCKS\r\n\r\n"
		)
		s.sendall(request)
		
		# Receive and print response (first few lines)
		response = s.recv(4096)
		print(response.decode(errors="ignore"))
		
		s.close()
		○ Save and run it
			§ python3 simple_socks_client.py
		○ 
	- Capture Traffic Like Before with tcpdump on the router
		○ tcpdump -i any -n tcp and \(port 22 or port 1080 or port 80\)

Task 3: Virtual Private Network (VPN) 
Task 3.1: Bypassing Ingress Firewall using VPN over SSH
		○ Goal: create an encrypted VPN tunnel between host A (10.8.0.99) and host B (192.168.20.99) so that packets can move freely between the external and internal networks despite the router's ingress rules blocking most inbound TCP traffic
	- Verify SSH permissions on B
		○ docker exec -it B-192.168.20.99 bash
		○ grep -E "PermitRootLogin|PermitTunnel" /etc/ssh/sshd_config
		○ Should say "PermitRootLogin yes" and "PermitTunnel yes"
	- Create the VPN tunnel from A to B
		○ docker exec -it A-10.8.0.99 bash
		○ ssh -w 0:0 root@192.168.20.99 \
		  "PermitLocalCommand=yes" \
		  "LocalCommand=ip addr add 192.168.53.88/24 dev tun0 && ip link set tun0 up" \
		  "RemoteCommand=ip addr add 192.168.53.99/24 dev tun0 && ip link set tun0 up"
		○ After running, it will ask for your root password
	- Capture Packets on Router
		○ docker exec -it router-firewall bash
		○ tcpdump -i any -n host 192.168.53.99 or host 192.168.53.88 
	- Test VPN Connectivity from A to B, B1, B2
		○ telnet 192.168.20.99 23
		○ telnet 192.168.20.5 23
		○ telnet 192.168.20.6 23
		○ Go back to router and view captured packets
	- Questions
		○ The VPN disguises all traffic as permitted SSH traffic
Task 3.2: Bypassing Egress Firewall 
	- Create the VPN tunnel with B as client and A as server
		○ Run on B
		○ docker exec -it B-192.168.20.99 bash
		○ ssh -w 0:0 root@10.8.0.99 \
		  -o "PermitLocalCommand=yes" \
		  -o "LocalCommand=ip tuntap add dev tun0 mode tun; ip addr add 192.168.53.88/24 dev tun0; ip link set tun0 up" \
		  -o "RemoteCommand=ip tuntap add dev tun0 mode tun; ip addr add 192.168.53.99/24 dev tun0; ip link set tun0 up"
		○ Enter password
